SIMPLE: thunder
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thunder
<hw>Thun"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧under</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧onder</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧oner</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧unor</ets>; akin to
<ets>⟦thorn⟧unian</ets> to stretch, to thunder, D. <ets>donder</ets>
thunder, G. <ets>donner</ets>, OHG. <ets>donar</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦omac⟧rr</ets> Thor, L. <ets>tonare</ets> to thunder,
<ets>tonitrus</ets> thunder, Gr. <grk>to`nos</grk> a stretching,
straining, Skr. <ets>tan</ets> to stretch. ⟦root⟧52. See <er>Thin</er>,
and cf. <er>Astonish</er>, <er>Detonate</er>, <er>Intone</er>,
<er>Thursday</er>, <er>Tone</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The sound
which follows a flash of lightning; the report of a discharge of
atmospheric electricity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The discharge of electricity; a thunderbolt.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The revenging gods⟦br⟧
'Gainst parricides did all their <qex>thunders</qex> bend.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any loud noise; <as>as, the <ex>thunder</ex> of
cannon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An alarming or statrling threat or
denunciation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>thunders</qex> of the Vatican could no longer strike into
the heart of princes.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thunder pumper</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>The croaker (<spn>Haploidontus grunniens</spn>).</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>The American bittern or stake-driver.</cd> -- <col><b>Thunder
rod</b></col>, <cd>a lightning rod.</cd> <mark>[R.]</mark> --
<col><b>Thunder snake</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The
chicken, or milk, snake.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A small reddish ground
snake (<spn>Carphophis amoena</spn> syn. <spn>Celuta amoena</spn>)
native to the Eastern United States; -- called also <altname>worm
snake</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Thunder tube</b></col>, <cd>a
fulgurite. See <er>Fulgurite</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thunder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thunder
<hw>Thun"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Thundered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Thundering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧unrian</ets>. See <er>Thunder</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To produce thunder; to sound, rattle, or roar, as a
discharge of atmospheric electricity; -- often used impersonally;
<as>as, it <ex>thundered</ex> continuously</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Canst thou <qex>thunder</qex> with a voice like him?</q>
<rj><qau>Job xl. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To make a loud noise; esp. a heavy sound, of
some continuance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His dreadful voice no more⟦br⟧
Would <qex>thunder</qex> in my ears.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To utter violent denunciation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thunder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thunder
<hw>Thun"der</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To emit with noise and terror;
to utter vehemently; to publish, as a threat or denunciation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oracles severe⟦br⟧
Were daily <qex>thundered</qex> in our general's ear.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An archdeacon, as being a prelate, may <qex>thunder</qex> out an
ecclesiastical censure.</q> <rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thunderbird</ent>⟦br⟧
